[
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644660",
        "quote": "Once we accept violence as an adaptation, it makes sense that its expression is calibrated to the environment. The same individual will behave differently if he comes of age in Detroit, Mich., versus Windsor, Ontario; in New York in the 1980s versus New York now; in a culture of honor versus a culture of dignity.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644660"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Honor",
                "url": "/topics/honor"
            },
            {
                "name": "Adaptation",
                "url": "/topics/adaptation"
            },
            {
                "name": "Behave",
                "url": "/topics/behave"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644663",
        "quote": "Modern science tells us that the conscious self arises from a purely physical brain. We do not have immaterial souls.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644663"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Brain",
                "url": "/topics/brain"
            },
            {
                "name": "Souls",
                "url": "/topics/souls"
            },
            {
                "name": "Purely",
                "url": "/topics/purely"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644664",
        "quote": "I don't doubt that the explanation for consciousness will arise from the mercilessly scientific account of psychology and neuroscience, but, still, isn't it neat that the universe is such that it gave rise to conscious beings like you and me?",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644664"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Consciousness",
                "url": "/topics/consciousness"
            },
            {
                "name": "Will",
                "url": "/topics/will"
            },
            {
                "name": "Still",
                "url": "/topics/still"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644668",
        "quote": "In politics and in society, we can use our reason to rise above our parochial natures. Too bad that our elected officials don't choose to do so more often.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644668"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Politics",
                "url": "/topics/politics"
            },
            {
                "name": "Reason",
                "url": "/topics/reason"
            },
            {
                "name": "Natures",
                "url": "/topics/natures"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644666",
        "quote": "We are constituted so that simple acts of kindness, such as giving to charity or expressing gratitude, have a positive effect on our long-term moods. The key to the happy life, it seems, is the good life: a life with sustained relationships, challenging work, and connections to community.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644666"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Happy",
                "url": "/topics/happy"
            },
            {
                "name": "Simple",
                "url": "/topics/simple"
            },
            {
                "name": "Expressing",
                "url": "/topics/expressing"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644654",
        "quote": "Some of the natural world is appealing, some of it is terrifying, and some of it grosses us out. Modern people don't want to be dropped naked into a swamp. We want to tour Yosemite with our water bottles and G.P.S. devices. The natural world is a source of happiness and fulfillment, but only when prescribed in the right doses.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644654"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Some",
                "url": "/topics/some"
            },
            {
                "name": "Terrifying",
                "url": "/topics/terrifying"
            },
            {
                "name": "Doses",
                "url": "/topics/doses"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644667",
        "quote": "Periods of cooperation between political parties shouldn't be taken for granted; they are a stunning human achievement.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644667"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Achievement",
                "url": "/topics/achievement"
            },
            {
                "name": "Political",
                "url": "/topics/political"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644648",
        "quote": "Humans are social beings, and we are happier, and better, when connected to others.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644648"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Better",
                "url": "/topics/better"
            },
            {
                "name": "Connected",
                "url": "/topics/connected"
            },
            {
                "name": "Happier",
                "url": "/topics/happier"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644639",
        "quote": "Relying on the face might be human nature - even babies prefer to look at attractive people. But, of course, judging someone based on the geometry of his features is, from a moral and legal standpoint, no better than judging him based on the color of his skin.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644639"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Color",
                "url": "/topics/color"
            },
            {
                "name": "Skin",
                "url": "/topics/skin"
            },
            {
                "name": "Prefer",
                "url": "/topics/prefer"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644656",
        "quote": "Humans are born with a hard-wired morality: a sense of good and evil is bred in the bone. I know this claim might sound outlandish, but it's supported now by research in several laboratories.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644656"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Born",
                "url": "/topics/born"
            },
            {
                "name": "Bred",
                "url": "/topics/bred"
            },
            {
                "name": "Might",
                "url": "/topics/might"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644629",
        "quote": "If our moral attitudes are entirely the result of nonrational factors, such as gut feelings and the absorption of cultural norms, they should either be stable or randomly drift over time, like skirt lengths or the widths of ties. They shouldn't show systematic change over human history. But they do.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644629"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Gut",
                "url": "/topics/gut"
            },
            {
                "name": "Show",
                "url": "/topics/show"
            },
            {
                "name": "Attitudes",
                "url": "/topics/attitudes"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644657",
        "quote": "We are naturally moral beings, but our environments can enhance - or, sadly, degrade - this innate moral sense.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644657"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Innate",
                "url": "/topics/innate"
            },
            {
                "name": "Sadly",
                "url": "/topics/sadly"
            },
            {
                "name": "Environments",
                "url": "/topics/environments"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644617",
        "quote": "Too often, our concern for specific individuals today means neglecting crises that will harm countless people in the future.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644617"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Means",
                "url": "/topics/means"
            },
            {
                "name": "Crises",
                "url": "/topics/crises"
            },
            {
                "name": "Neglecting",
                "url": "/topics/neglecting"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644621",
        "quote": "One way to make a baby cry is to expose it to cries of other babies. There's sort of contagiousness to the crying. It's not just crying. We also know that if a baby sees another human in silent pain, it will distress the baby. It seems part of our very nature is to suffer at the suffering of others.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644621"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Distress",
                "url": "/topics/distress"
            },
            {
                "name": "Very",
                "url": "/topics/very"
            },
            {
                "name": "Other",
                "url": "/topics/other"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644618",
        "quote": "Our best hope for the future is not to get people to think of all humanity as family - that's impossible. It lies, instead, in an appreciation of the fact that, even if we don't empathize with distant strangers, their lives have the same value as the lives of those we love.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644618"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Love",
                "url": "/topics/love"
            },
            {
                "name": "Impossible",
                "url": "/topics/impossible"
            },
            {
                "name": "Fact",
                "url": "/topics/fact"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644658",
        "quote": "The enjoyment we get from something is powerfully influenced by what we think that thing really is. This is true for intellectual pleasures, such as the appreciation of paintings and stories, and it is true as well for pleasures that seem simpler and more animalistic, such as the satisfaction of hunger and lust.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644658"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Influenced",
                "url": "/topics/influenced"
            },
            {
                "name": "Animalistic",
                "url": "/topics/animalistic"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644662",
        "quote": "The irrationality of disgust suggests it is unreliable as a source of moral insight. There may be good arguments against gay marriage, partial-birth abortions and human cloning, but the fact that some people find such acts to be disgusting should carry no weight.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644662"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Fact",
                "url": "/topics/fact"
            },
            {
                "name": "Some",
                "url": "/topics/some"
            },
            {
                "name": "Irrationality",
                "url": "/topics/irrationality"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644653",
        "quote": "Natural selection shaped the human brain to be drawn toward aspects of nature that enhance our survival and reproduction, like verdant landscapes and docile creatures. There is no payoff to getting the warm fuzzies in the presence of rats, snakes, mosquitoes, cockroaches, herpes simplex and the rabies virus.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644653"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Shaped",
                "url": "/topics/shaped"
            },
            {
                "name": "Aspects",
                "url": "/topics/aspects"
            },
            {
                "name": "Docile",
                "url": "/topics/docile"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644616",
        "quote": "On many issues, empathy can pull us in the wrong direction. The outrage that comes from adopting the perspective of a victim can drive an appetite for retribution.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644616"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Empathy",
                "url": "/topics/empathy"
            },
            {
                "name": "Wrong Direction",
                "url": "/topics/wrong_direction"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644615",
        "quote": "Empathy has some unfortunate features - it is parochial, narrow-minded, and innumerate. We're often at our best when we're smart enough not to rely on it.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644615"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Empathy",
                "url": "/topics/empathy"
            },
            {
                "name": "Some",
                "url": "/topics/some"
            },
            {
                "name": "Unfortunate",
                "url": "/topics/unfortunate"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644623",
        "quote": "We'd be really screwed if we had to start our life over again as children with our brains right now, because I think we lose the plasticity and flexibility.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644623"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Think",
                "url": "/topics/think"
            },
            {
                "name": "Screwed",
                "url": "/topics/screwed"
            },
            {
                "name": "Over",
                "url": "/topics/over"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644614",
        "quote": "Maybe one of the most heartening findings from the psychology of pleasure is there's more to looking good than your physical appearance. If you like somebody, they look better to you. This is why spouses in happy marriages tend to think that their husband or wife looks much better than anyone else thinks that they do.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644614"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Happy",
                "url": "/topics/happy"
            },
            {
                "name": "Why",
                "url": "/topics/why"
            },
            {
                "name": "Maybe",
                "url": "/topics/maybe"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644632",
        "quote": "More-radical scholars insist that an inherent clash exists between science and our long-held conceptions about consciousness and moral agency: if you accept that our brains are a myriad of smaller components, you must reject such notions as character, praise, blame, and free will.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644632"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Clash",
                "url": "/topics/clash"
            },
            {
                "name": "Smaller",
                "url": "/topics/smaller"
            },
            {
                "name": "Components",
                "url": "/topics/components"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644637",
        "quote": "The real problem with natural selection is that it makes no intuitive sense. It is like quantum physics; we may intellectually grasp it, but it will never feel right to us.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644637"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "May",
                "url": "/topics/may"
            },
            {
                "name": "Natural",
                "url": "/topics/natural"
            },
            {
                "name": "Like",
                "url": "/topics/like"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644661",
        "quote": "If our wondrous kindness is evidence for God, is our capacity for great evil proof of the Devil?",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644661"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Devil",
                "url": "/topics/devil"
            },
            {
                "name": "Wondrous",
                "url": "/topics/wondrous"
            },
            {
                "name": "Great Evil",
                "url": "/topics/great_evil"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644630",
        "quote": "Most of us know nothing about constitutional law, so it's hardly surprising that we take sides in the Obamacare debate the way we root for the Red Sox or the Yankees. Loyalty to the team is what matters.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644630"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Law",
                "url": "/topics/law"
            },
            {
                "name": "Nothing",
                "url": "/topics/nothing"
            },
            {
                "name": "Red Sox",
                "url": "/topics/red_sox"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644646",
        "quote": "Perhaps looking out through big baby eyes - if we could - would not be as revelatory experience as many imagine. We might see a world inhabited by objects and people, a world infused with causation, agency, and morality - a world that would surprise us not by its freshness but by its familiarity.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644646"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Through",
                "url": "/topics/through"
            },
            {
                "name": "Big",
                "url": "/topics/big"
            },
            {
                "name": "Familiarity",
                "url": "/topics/familiarity"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644650",
        "quote": "The emotions triggered by fiction are very real. When Charles Dickens wrote about the death of Little Nell in the 1840s, people wept - and I'm sure that the death of characters in J.K. Rowling's 'Harry Potter' series led to similar tears.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644650"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Death",
                "url": "/topics/death"
            },
            {
                "name": "Tears",
                "url": "/topics/tears"
            },
            {
                "name": "Very",
                "url": "/topics/very"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644628",
        "quote": "Strong moral arguments exist for why we should often try to ignore stereotypes or override them. But we shouldn't assume they represent some irrational quirk of the unconscious mind. In fact, they're largely the consequence of the mind's attempt to make a rational decision.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644628"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Strong",
                "url": "/topics/strong"
            },
            {
                "name": "Fact",
                "url": "/topics/fact"
            },
            {
                "name": "Some",
                "url": "/topics/some"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644644",
        "quote": "Imagination tends to be truly useful if accompanied by the power of mental control - if the worlds in one's head can be purposefully manipulated and distinguished from the real one outside it.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644644"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Control",
                "url": "/topics/control"
            },
            {
                "name": "Worlds",
                "url": "/topics/worlds"
            },
            {
                "name": "Mental",
                "url": "/topics/mental"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644645",
        "quote": "Empty heads, cognitive science has taught us, learn nothing. The powerful cultural and personal flexibility of our species is owed at least in part to our starting off so well-informed; we are good learners because we know what to pay attention to and what questions are the right ones to ask.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644645"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Part",
                "url": "/topics/part"
            },
            {
                "name": "Well-Informed",
                "url": "/topics/well-informed"
            },
            {
                "name": "Least",
                "url": "/topics/least"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644665",
        "quote": "If evil is empathy erosion, and empathy erosion is a form of illness, then evil turns out to be nothing more than a particularly awful psychological disorder.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644665"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Empathy",
                "url": "/topics/empathy"
            },
            {
                "name": "More",
                "url": "/topics/more"
            },
            {
                "name": "Particularly",
                "url": "/topics/particularly"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644613",
        "quote": "I want to convince you that humans are, to some extent, natural born essentialists. What I mean by this is we don't just respond to things as we see them or feel them or hear them. Rather, our response is conditioned on our beliefs, about what they really are, what they came from, what they're made of, what their hidden nature is.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644613"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Hidden",
                "url": "/topics/hidden"
            },
            {
                "name": "Some",
                "url": "/topics/some"
            },
            {
                "name": "Extent",
                "url": "/topics/extent"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644619",
        "quote": "It's really difficult working with kids and with babies because they are not cooperative subjects: they are not socialized into the idea that they should cheerfully and cooperatively give you information. They're not like undergraduates, who you can bribe with beer money or course credit.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644619"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Idea",
                "url": "/topics/idea"
            },
            {
                "name": "Bribe",
                "url": "/topics/bribe"
            },
            {
                "name": "Babies",
                "url": "/topics/babies"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644620",
        "quote": "Having kids has proven to be this amazing - for me, this amazing source of ideas of anecdotes, of examples, I can test my own kids without human subject permission, so they pilot - I pilot my ideas on them. And so it is a tremendous advantage to have kids if you're going to be a developmental psychologist.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644620"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Own",
                "url": "/topics/own"
            },
            {
                "name": "Subject",
                "url": "/topics/subject"
            },
            {
                "name": "Developmental",
                "url": "/topics/developmental"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644622",
        "quote": "We know that young babies, as they become capable of moving voluntarily, will share. They will share food, for instance, with their siblings and with kids that are around. They will sooth. If they see somebody else in pain, even the youngest of toddlers will try to reach out and pat the person.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
            "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644622"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Young",
                "url": "/topics/young"
            },
            {
                "name": "Toddlers",
                "url": "/topics/toddlers"
            },
            {
                "name": "Instance",
                "url": "/topics/instance"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/paul_bloom_644624",
        "quote": "You'd expect, as good Darwinian creatures, we would evolve to be fascinated with how the world really is, and we would use language to convey real-world information, we'd be obsessed with knowing the way things are, and we would entirely reject stories that aren't true. They're useless. But that's not the way we work.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Paul Bloom",
